(## 5.5 Concurrency Model) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This project uses the Category 1 concurrency model of one parent controller process ) Tj
T*
(coordinating a fixed pool of child worker processes. The parent creates concurrency at ) Tj
T*
(startup by spawning all three workers before any file-analysis tasks are processed. This ) Tj
T*
(setup is implemented in spawn_worker\(\) at controller.c:182, which first creates two pipes ) Tj
T*
(for each worker and then calls fork so that the child inherits the pipe file descriptors it ) Tj
T*
(needs. After the fork, the child keeps only the read end of its task pipe and the write end ) Tj
T*
(of its result pipe, while the parent keeps only the write end of the task pipe and the read ) Tj
T*
(end of the result pipe. Because run_controller\(\) at controller.c:481 creates all three ) Tj
T*
(children before entering the main dispatch loop, at least three workers exist concurrently ) Tj
T*
(during execution, satisfying the assignment requirement.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The parent does not use mutexes, signals, or shared memory to coordinate work. Instead, ) Tj
T*
(synchronization is provided entirely by pipe-based message passing and a small amount of ) Tj
T*
(controller state. A worker is considered ready when it is alive and its busy flag is clear. ) Tj
T*
(In practice, that means the parent has either just created the worker or has already ) Tj
T*
(received that worker's previous result and marked it idle again. The ) Tj
T*
(dispatch_pending_tasks\(\) function at controller.c:326 scans the worker table for idle ) Tj
T*
(workers and the task table for queued files, then sends one TaskMessage to each available ) Tj
T*
(worker through dispatch_task_to_worker\(\) at controller.c:292. Once a task is assigned, the ) Tj
T*
(controller marks that worker as busy and records which task is currently in flight for that ) Tj
T*
(process.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Each worker runs a simple loop in worker_main_loop\(\) at worker.c:45. It blocks in ) Tj
T*
(read_full\(\) at ipc.c:7 waiting for the next TaskMessage from the controller, processes the ) Tj
T*
(requested file through process_task_message\(\) at worker.c:14, sends back exactly one ) Tj
T*
(ResultMessage, and then returns to the blocking read state. This design keeps the worker ) Tj
T*
(logic simple while still allowing multiple files to be analyzed at the same time in ) Tj
T*
(different processes. The blocking read on the task pipe is sufficient to synchronize each ) Tj
T*
(worker with the controller, because an idle worker naturally sleeps until new work arrives.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(On the parent side, results are collected concurrently using poll in collect_ready_results\(\)) Tj
T*
( at controller.c:399. Before each wait, the controller builds an array of pollfd structures ) Tj
T*
(containing the read end of every live result pipe and asks poll to block until one or more ) Tj
T*
(workers either produce a result or disconnect. This avoids waiting on workers in a fixed ) Tj
T*
(order and ensures that the parent reacts to whichever worker finishes first. When poll ) Tj
T*
(reports input on a result pipe, the controller reads exactly one ResultMessage, verifies ) Tj
T*
(that it matches the expected in-flight task for that worker in mark_task_completed\(\) at ) Tj
T*
(controller.c:350, records the result, marks the worker idle, and immediately makes that ) Tj
T*
(worker available for another queued task.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Child processes are collected with waitpid through reap_worker_if_possible\(\) at ) Tj
T*
(controller.c:115. If a worker fails during execution, the controller closes its pipe ) Tj
ET
endstream
